00:15:24,404 --> 00:15:26,623
- Repeat message 5-B.
- Wait!

242
00:15:26,739 --> 00:15:29,160
You guys broke up, right?

243
00:15:31,598 --> 00:15:36,091
- I think I left my phone at the coffeshop.
- You went to a coffeeshop?

244
00:15:36,207 --> 00:15:38,971
I thought that you already had your coffee?

245
00:15:39,085 --> 00:15:41,470
- That's very interesting.
- Can I use yours?

246
00:15:41,588 --> 00:15:45,301
Oh, boy! I think that I should
conserve battery power.

247
00:15:45,425 --> 00:15:46,718
Please.

248
00:15:46,843 --> 00:15:48,100
Oh!

249
00:15:48,219 --> 00:15:50,355
Okay. Make it snappy.

250
00:15:50,471 --> 00:15:52,607
Wait. Seriously, this is
what you use to call people?

251
00:15:52,724 --> 00:15:55,523
- Okay, listen, if you don't want to use it...
- No, no. It's fine.

252
00:15:55,643 --> 00:15:57,731
I just, uh...

253
00:15:57,854 --> 00:15:59,989
- Uh...
- You don't know her number?

254
00:16:00,106 --> 00:16:02,610
No! I... Ssh! All right? I'm trying to think.

255
00:16:02,734 --> 00:16:05,533
The prospects for your relationship
are not looking good.

256
00:16:05,653 --> 00:16:08,038
I always just use speed dial, all right?
Everybody does that.

257
00:16:08,156 --> 00:16:09,709
Listen, no one is judging you.

258
00:16:09,824 --> 00:16:13,170
I'm just saying that when I care about someone,
I commit their phone number to memory.

259
00:16:13,286 --> 00:16:14,876
Like my mom.

260
00:16:14,996 --> 00:16:19,293
Oh, shark, my mom!
Gimme-gimme-gimme-gimme-gimme!

261
00:16:26,007 --> 00:16:27,644
- Hello?
- Mom!

262
00:16:27,759 --> 00:16:30,891
- Are there zombies there?
- Gotcha! You've reached my voicemail.

263
00:16:31,012 --> 00:16:33,812
- Please leave a message.
- Jesus, Mom, I hate this gag.

264
00:16:33,932 --> 00:16:35,937
Just kidding, it's actually me.

265
00:16:36,059 --> 00:16:38,906
Oh, oh... Mom, are you really there?

266
00:16:39,020 --> 00:16:42,448
Well, of course, little Miss Magoo.
Happy Fourth of July!

267
00:16:42,565 --> 00:16:45,531
Uh, have you been outside yet today?

268
00:16:45,652 --> 00:16:47,573
Why, yes, I was just down
at the Pick 'n Save.

269
00:16:47,695 --> 00:16:49,747
And are there people
eating other people's flesh?

270
00:16:49,864 --> 00:16:51,704
I'm in Virginia Beach, honey, not Florida.

271
00:16:51,824 --> 00:16:55,621
Mom, listen to me. The people here
are infected with something.

272
00:16:55,745 --> 00:16:58,130
I'm trying to get down there,
but if I don't make it...

273
00:16:59,207 --> 00:17:01,010
- ...take care of yourself.
- Deb?

274
00:17:01,125 --> 00:17:02,679
- I love you.
- Are you there?

275
00:17:02,794 --> 00:17:04,799
- Ma?
- Can you hear me?

276
00:17:06,089 --> 00:17:09,265
- Still using that janky old phon...
- Dammit!

277
00:17:17,183 --> 00:17:18,441
Mm.

278
00:17:21,938 --> 00:17:25,681
Okay, let's take stock of
what we have and, uh...

279
00:17:27,569 --> 00:17:31,875
Board up the windows. Way ahead
of you, chief. Pee corner's over there.

280
00:17:31,990 --> 00:17:35,952
That end table was a matching set! And we
don't need a pee corner, I've got a bathr...

281
00:17:36,077 --> 00:17:38,708
You know what? We're getting out of here.

282
00:17:40,832 --> 00:17:43,382
Help me!

283
00:17:48,381 --> 00:17:51,264
All right, they're drawn to the noise.
We'll have to leave quietly.

284
00:17:51,384 --> 00:17:53,436
But... you heard the radio.

285
00:17:53,553 --> 00:17:57,065
They said to hunker down and wait for
the National Guard or, you know, whatever.

286
00:17:57,182 --> 00:17:59,436
And, just some food for thought,

287
00:17:59,559 --> 00:18:02,987
we might want to start bonding
in case we have to repopulate the world.

288
00:18:03,104 --> 00:18:06,486
- Just thinking out loud here.
- No, please don't, all right?

289
00:18:06,608 --> 00:18:10,321
Look, my fiancée, brother and father
are out there. They'll be expecting me.

290
00:18:10,445 --> 00:18:13,707
Breaking news... people are kind of
foregoing their holiday plans right now.

291
00:18:13,823 --> 00:18:15,460
You'll be no help to them
if you get infected.

292
00:18:15,575 --> 00:18:18,921
I'd rather take that risk than be
without the people I care about.

293
00:18:19,037 --> 00:18:22,964
- Okay, whatever you want. I'm staying put.
- But I need you!

294
00:18:25,460 --> 00:18:30,181
It's weird. I know that we've only known
each other a short time, but I kind of feel...

295
00:18:30,298 --> 00:18:32,766
- You have a car.
- Oh?

296
00:18:32,884 --> 00:18:35,684
What happened to yours, player?
It's in the shop?

297
00:18:35,803 --> 00:18:38,188
I don't have one.
I ride my bicycle everywhere.

298
00:18:38,306 --> 00:18:41,438
Everywhere except across town in
the middle of a zombie apocalypse, huh?

299
00:18:41,559 --> 00:18:43,529
- Is that your one exception?
- Look...

300
00:18:43,645 --> 00:18:46,325
Help me collect my people,
then we can all leave town together,

301
00:18:46,439 --> 00:18:49,120
and then you can get to your mom in Virginia.

302
00:18:49,234 --> 00:18:50,954
Oh, I can't stay mad at you!

303
00:18:52,237 --> 00:18:54,407
We're gonna need some road snacks.

304
00:18:54,531 --> 00:18:57,414
Oh! I foolishly thought
that you kept food in here.

305
00:18:57,534 --> 00:19:01,591
- Hey, we can survive on this stuff!
- Oh, for an hour, if we were rabbits.

306
00:19:01,704 --> 00:19:04,670
Why do you have coconut water?
Is this Maine or Gilligan's Island?

307
00:19:04,791 --> 00:19:07,259
It's very hydrating.

308
00:19:07,377 --> 00:19:10,971
Okay, once we get in that car,
I am not stopping till we get to VA.

309
00:19:11,089 --> 00:19:13,557
There's gotta be some place
around here that we can get food.

310
00:19:13,675 --> 00:19:17,732
I check in on Mrs Jones,
get her groceries once in a while.

311
00:19:17,846 --> 00:19:20,064
Oh, that's so sweet!

312
00:19:22,308 --> 00:19:23,898
Oh, no!

313
00:19:25,895 --> 00:19:27,781
Oh, my God! Is she...

314
00:19:30,233 --> 00:19:31,823
So sad!

315
00:19:31,943 --> 00:19:34,078
To die alone on the Fourth.

316
00:19:36,573 --> 00:19:38,245
Shadows are trailing.

317
00:19:38,366 --> 00:19:40,169
My heart is bewailing.

318
00:19:40,285 --> 00:19:42,586
And tolling within like a funeral bell.

319
00:19:43,788 --> 00:19:46,007
Rest in peace, Mrs Jones.

320
00:19:49,502 --> 00:19:51,472
What are you doing?

321
00:19:51,588 --> 00:19:54,684
Oh, I was just reciting some Longfellow.
I think it's nice to say...

322
00:19:54,799 --> 00:19:57,018
No, no. Why did you open her eyes?

323
00:19:57,135 --> 00:20:01,975
That's what you do when someone dies,
to let their soul rise up to heaven.

324
00:20:02,098 --> 00:20:05,361
What? No, no. You close their eyes.

325
00:20:05,476 --> 00:20:08,525
Uh, okay, trust me on this one!

326
00:20:08,646 --> 00:20:12,241
No. Trust me. Okay? Nobody does it that way.

327
00:20:12,358 --> 00:20:16,238
Uh, you're gonna feel pretty silly
when the internet's back up.

328
00:20:16,362 --> 00:20:20,669
Please! This was a sweet old lady,
all right? Don't be weird.

329
00:20:20,783 --> 00:20:22,586
Just leave her in peace.

330
00:20:22,702 --> 00:20:24,375
- I...
- Stop it!

331
00:20:24,495 --> 00:20:26,465
Ooh, taking control!

332
00:20:26,581 --> 00:20:30,128
Yeah, I dig it!
But I've gotta do right by her.

333
00:20:30,251 --> 00:20:32,470
Let your soul be free!

334
00:20:32,587 --> 00:20:35,552
- You're being ridiculous.
- No, you're being ridiculous!

335
00:20:35,673 --> 00:20:38,141
And let go of my wrist, you're hurting me.

336
00:20:38,259 --> 00:20:41,392
- I'm not touching your... Whoa!
- What is happening?

337
00:20:43,890 --> 00:20:46,738
- A little help here, chief!
- I'm working on it!

338
00:20:47,060 --> 00:20:48,903
Okay, I'm sorry, Mrs Jones.

339
00:20:49,020 --> 00:20:52,698
- I'm really sorry to do this to you.
- Forget the lamp, Martha Stewart!

340
00:20:52,815 --> 00:20:55,236
Okay! Okay, okay! Jump away!

341
00:20:55,360 --> 00:20:57,910
All right! Now, and...

342
00:20:58,029 --> 00:20:59,666
- Clear!
- What are you doing?

343
00:20:59,781 --> 00:21:02,249
What? Why isn't it working?
Deb, do something!

344
00:21:02,367 --> 00:21:05,084
Please don't struggle, Mrs Jones!

345
00:21:05,203 --> 00:21:07,089
Oh! She's old!

346
00:21:15,129 --> 00:21:17,182
- Yeah!
- All right!

347
00:21:18,842 --> 00:21:22,021
I mean, that was a terrible, actually,
cos she was my neighbour.

348
00:21:22,136 --> 00:21:25,066
But that's, uh... Let's get the food.

349
00:21:31,020 --> 00:21:34,671
These are the crappiest snacks.
Didn't this lady eat any solids?

350
00:21:39,195 --> 00:21:40,406
Whoa!

351
00:21:40,530 --> 00:21:43,116
At least they're three floors down.

352
00:21:44,617 --> 00:21:47,583
Aah! Fire escape! Fire escape!

353
00:21:54,043 --> 00:21:56,013
Wait! Slow down!

354
00:21:56,129 --> 00:21:58,430
What are you doing?
You should've left all that stuff!

355
00:21:58,548 --> 00:22:00,885
- Sorry. Fine!
- No, no, no, don't just...

356
00:22:01,009 --> 00:22:02,765
Sorry.

357
00:22:02,886 --> 00:22:04,060
Shit!

358
00:22:04,179 --> 00:22:06,266
Great! Now look what you made me do.

359
00:22:11,519 --> 00:22:13,939
Well, that's it. We're toast.

360
00:22:14,063 --> 00:22:16,531
It's stupid for us both to die.

361
00:22:18,359 --> 00:22:20,661
- I'm gonna give you a chance.
- What are you talking about?

362
00:22:20,778 --> 00:22:21,822
Ssh!

363
00:22:21,946 --> 00:22:24,165
Earn this. Huh?

364
00:22:27,076 --> 00:22:29,331
- Come on.
- When the moment is right,

365
00:22:29,454 --> 00:22:31,293
you grab your bike and go!

366
00:22:31,414 --> 00:22:33,336
Who wants a piece of this?

367
00:22:46,262 --> 00:22:48,564
Why are you hitting yourself?
Why are you hitting yourself?

368
00:22:48,681 --> 00:22:50,936
Why are you hitting yourself?

369
00:22:51,059 --> 00:22:53,278
Here, guys. I'm right here.

370
00:22:53,394 --> 00:22:55,400
Come on, you guys, get over here.

371
00:22:55,522 --> 00:22:57,906
Come on, you guys. I'm just right here.

372
00:22:58,024 --> 00:22:59,282
Hey!

373
00:23:06,157 --> 00:23:07,450
Whoa!

374
00:23:07,575 --> 00:23:08,749
Aah!

375
00:23:08,868 --> 00:23:11,917
That was awesome! You were awesome!

376
00:23:12,038 --> 00:23:13,960
I feel so alive!

377
00:23:14,082 --> 00:23:16,169
- Tell me you have your keys.
- Yes!

378
00:23:24,759 --> 00:23:28,390
You saved me, Ryan! You effing saved me!

379
00:23:28,513 --> 00:23:31,941
I think we can be pretty sure
that you like me.

380
00:23:32,058 --> 00:23:33,944
Good, God! Do you live in here?

381
00:23:34,060 --> 00:23:35,448
No!

382
00:23:37,522 --> 00:23:39,112
Not any more.

383
00:23:39,232 --> 00:23:41,284
Maybe there's something more
about this on the radio.

384
00:23:41,401 --> 00:23:43,904
Don't you ever touch a black man's radio!

385
00:23:44,028 --> 00:23:46,365
It's Chris Tucker, Rush Hour.

386
00:23:46,489 --> 00:23:48,743
Radio's busted. Tape player works, though.

387
00:23:48,867 --> 00:23:51,999
Oh, well, that's completely useless.

388
00:23:53,496 --> 00:23:55,003
Ten points!

389
00:23:55,123 --> 00:23:57,258
W-w-what are you doing?

390
00:23:57,375 --> 00:23:59,012
I know! Low hanging fruit, right?

391
00:24:00,295 --> 00:24:02,264
Aah! No, no! Stop that.

392
00:24:02,380 --> 00:24:05,844
Don't worry about it! This is like
swatting mosquitoes for little Otis.

393
00:24:05,967 --> 00:24:09,561
No, no! You can't just murder these zombies.
These are people.

394
00:24:09,679 --> 00:24:12,064
Um... maybe they were once.

395
00:24:12,182 --> 00:24:14,946
No. For all we know, some chemist
could be working on a cure right now.

396
00:24:15,059 --> 00:24:16,447
- They could be turned normal again.
- Sure!

397
00:24:16,561 --> 00:24:18,981
And maybe we can all hold hands
and skip to Yum-Yum Town,

398
00:24:19,105 --> 00:24:21,739
where rainbows shoot
out of the butts of unicorns.

399
00:24:21,858 --> 00:24:23,199
I'm serious.

400
00:24:24,319 --> 00:24:27,581
Ryan, even if you're right,
would they really want to come back?

401
00:24:27,697 --> 00:24:31,577
How would you deal with the fact that you
just ate your roommate's lower intestine?

402
00:24:31,701 --> 00:24:34,418
Okay, okay. I wasn't looking on that one.

403
00:24:34,537 --> 00:24:36,044
Please, Deb.

404
00:24:40,627 --> 00:24:42,762
Enjoy your life, zombies.

405
00:24:48,676 --> 00:24:51,891
I always knew this town was dead,
but this is ridiculous.

406
00:24:52,013 --> 00:24:53,686
Cha-cha-cha!

407
00:24:53,806 --> 00:24:55,609
How many miles does this boat get?

408
00:24:55,725 --> 00:24:57,944
Oh, you're gonna bust on my car now?

409
00:24:58,061 --> 00:25:01,525
No, no, I was just thinking about
when we need to fill up the gas again.

410
00:25:01,648 --> 00:25:05,871
No, no, I hear it in your voice.
"Otis is offensive. Otis is unclean."

411
00:25:05,985 --> 00:25:10,043
Do you know, like, what the emissions from
this car actually do to the environment?

412
00:25:10,156 --> 00:25:13,205
I'm sorry, I must have missed
that page in Ryan's Guide To Being

413
00:25:13,326 --> 00:25:15,627
- A Completely Perfect Humanoid.
- No, no!

414
00:25:15,745 --> 00:25:19,423
It's not about being perfect.
Clean energy is just the right thing to do.

415
00:25:19,541 --> 00:25:21,343
Energy is messy, okay.

416
00:25:21,459 --> 00:25:26,098
I mean, it's really cute to eat organic millet
and drive around in a hovercraft or whatever,

417
00:25:26,214 --> 00:25:28,219
but look around you, dude.

418
00:25:28,341 --> 00:25:31,723
We lost. We tried to save the planet
and this is where it got us.

419
00:25:31,845 --> 00:25:34,977
- God, you sound just like my dad.
- Really?

420
00:25:35,098 --> 00:25:37,518
The guy sounds awesome.
What are you, adopted?

421
00:25:37,642 --> 00:25:42,482
That's good. Nice one. That's actually the
family joke. My brother makes it all the time.

422
00:25:43,544 --> 00:25:49,723
It's a good one. Look, I'm sorry.
My family is not a Hallmark card either.

423
00:25:51,406 --> 00:25:53,577
I remember every Fourth,

424
00:25:53,700 --> 00:25:57,757
my dad would bring us all up to the roof
to watch fireworks over the eastern prom.

425
00:25:57,871 --> 00:26:02,841
And then, one year, around dusk,
the guy's nowhere to be found.

426
00:26:02,959 --> 00:26:07,016
So we go up to the roof
and that's when we saw him.

427
00:26:08,965 --> 00:26:12,180
He was lying there in the backyard,

428
00:26:12,302 --> 00:26:14,888
right by the barbecue.

429
00:26:15,013 --> 00:26:17,065
He almost looked like he was asleep.

430
00:26:19,517 --> 00:26:23,777
He was changing out the propane tank.
It was the best cookout ever.

431
00:26:26,316 --> 00:26:28,403
- That's the end of the story?
- Mm-hm.

432
00:26:28,526 --> 00:26:31,243
That's a ridiculous... That was so strange.

433
00:26:31,362 --> 00:26:33,699
- It's all going one direction and then...
- But that was a good memory.

434
00:26:33,823 --> 00:26:35,875
It's not all like that.

435
00:26:35,992 --> 00:26:37,914
It's a mixed bag.

436
00:26:38,036 --> 00:26:40,372
Okay, well, anyway, um...

437
00:26:41,456 --> 00:26:44,884
My dad is pissed because
I won't work for the family business.

438
00:26:45,001 --> 00:26:46,555
Really? What's wrong with it?

439
00:26:46,669 --> 00:26:50,596
It's rated the most environmentally
unsound business in the state.

440
00:26:50,715 --> 00:26:53,396
Waverly Water Treatment?

441
00:26:53,510 --> 00:26:55,930
You're a Waverly? Oh, my God!

442
00:26:56,054 --> 00:26:59,186
- How did you put that together?
- Because I work in the news, remember?

443
00:26:59,307 --> 00:27:03,816
Don't get me wrong, that company seems like
pure evil but the buckage must be pretty good.

444
00:27:03,937 --> 00:27:07,899
Yeah, well, not for me. I'm not gonna
work there, so my brother's gonna get it all.

445
00:27:08,024 --> 00:27:10,159
Mm, tough break.

446
00:27:10,276 --> 00:27:12,613
Where the fuck are we?

447
00:27:13,947 --> 00:27:15,749
Wait. What are you doing?

448
00:27:15,865 --> 00:27:18,001
Just gotta stop in here.

449
00:27:21,955 --> 00:27:24,885
Yule Mart? No, no, we agreed.

450
00:27:24,999 --> 00:27:27,680
No more stopping. My dad's place
is just a couple of miles up the road.

451
00:27:27,794 --> 00:27:31,970
Yeah, and we're gonna get there. But my
friend's inside. I have to see if she's okay.

452
00:27:32,090 --> 00:27:34,177
Fine. Five minutes.

453
00:27:34,300 --> 00:27:36,720
Do we have anything deadlier
than a bike chain?

454
00:27:37,804 --> 00:27:38,896
Uh...

455
00:27:39,013 --> 00:27:40,686
This... thing.

456
00:27:40,807 --> 00:27:41,851
No.

457
00:27:41,975 --> 00:27:44,194
Oh, check the glove box.

458
00:27:48,398 --> 00:27:50,319
Maybe that?

459
00:27:53,194 --> 00:27:56,540
You've had a gun this entire time?

460
00:27:56,656 --> 00:27:59,753
Yeah, it was in there when I bought the car.

461
00:27:59,868 --> 00:28:03,082
It's mostly for show, though,
it only has two bullets.

462
00:28:03,204 --> 00:28:06,004
If it comes down to it,
we'll use it to tap out.

463
00:28:06,124 --> 00:28:08,259
- "Tap out"?
- Yeah.

464
00:28:08,376 --> 00:28:10,713
You know, if we get infected.

465
00:28:10,837 --> 00:28:12,759
Tap. Poof!

466
00:28:12,881 --> 00:28:15,182
And then tap. Poof!

467
00:28:15,300 --> 00:28:17,601
You just shot yourself first.

468
00:28:17,719 --> 00:28:21,480
Oh, I'm sorry, Ryan! I haven't worked out
the math on our murder-suicide yet!

469
00:28:21,598 --> 00:28:23,816
Okay, let me be really clear about this.

470
00:28:23,933 --> 00:28:26,104
I do not want to be tapped out.

471
00:28:27,270 --> 00:28:28,991
Right, you say that now!

472
00:28:29,105 --> 00:28:33,067
No, seriously, if I get infected, just let me
run off into the woods or something.

473
00:28:33,193 --> 00:28:36,491
You'll feel differently when you get
infected. I don't want you to suffer.

474
00:28:36,613 --> 00:28:40,290
No, I could not be more sure about this.
I do not want you to shoot me in the head.

475
00:28:40,408 --> 00:28:43,125
Sure, sure, sure. Okay, okay.
We'll see, though.

476
00:28:43,244 --> 00:28:44,336
Okay?

477
00:28:50,168 --> 00:28:51,758
Stay alert.

478
00:28:54,881 --> 00:28:57,680
# Jingle bells, jingle bells...

479
00:28:58,510 --> 00:29:01,274
# Oh, what fun it is to ride... #

480
00:29:12,398 --> 00:29:14,119
# Deck the halls with... #

481
00:29:17,695 --> 00:29:20,828
- Look at all this crap.
- You don't like Christmas?

482
00:29:20,949 --> 00:29:23,832
Are you kidding, me?
I freakin' love Christmas.

483
00:29:23,952 --> 00:29:27,629
Which is why I think these plastic trees
are for Tyre stores and...

484
00:29:27,747 --> 00:29:29,669
communists.

485
00:29:29,791 --> 00:29:33,718
When I have kids, I'm gonna take them
every year to cut down a real tree.

486
00:29:33,837 --> 00:29:36,802
You realise it takes ten years
for one of those trees to grow

487
00:29:36,923 --> 00:29:38,679
and only seconds to saw the life out of it?

488
00:29:38,800 --> 00:29:41,481
If there's a bigger buzz-kill than you, sir,
I do not know what that looks like.

489
00:29:41,594 --> 00:29:44,892
I'm just saying that we should celebrate
planting a tree with the children,

490
00:29:45,014 --> 00:29:46,568
rather than destroying one.

491
00:29:46,683 --> 00:29:48,071
"We"?

492
00:29:48,184 --> 00:29:50,735
- Yeah, you know. I mean, people, Earth.
- A-huh.

493
00:29:50,854 --> 00:29:52,360
But you said "the children".

494
00:29:52,480 --> 00:29:54,485
If you meant children in general,
you would've said something like...

495
00:29:54,607 --> 00:29:56,328
Oh, my God!

496
00:29:56,442 --> 00:29:58,448
That sweater!

497
00:30:01,322 --> 00:30:02,746
Ruby?

498
00:30:02,866 --> 00:30:05,250
Honey, are you okay?

499
00:30:07,120 --> 00:30:08,876
Look out!

500
00:30:12,667 --> 00:30:15,004
Well, it looks like she's
full-on zombie, let's jet.

501
00:30:15,128 --> 00:30:18,615
- Wait! We can't leave her like that.
- What do you suggest?

502
00:30:19,257 --> 00:30:22,894
- Tap, tap.
- Use our bullets on her?

503
00:30:23,011 --> 00:30:25,894
It's the right thing to do. Besides,
you said you don't want to use them.

504
00:30:26,014 --> 00:30:27,307
But the gun's in the car.

505
00:30:31,102 --> 00:30:32,490
Here.

506
00:30:32,604 --> 00:30:34,656
You distract her and lead her outside.

507
00:30:34,772 --> 00:30:36,445
I'll do the rest.

508
00:30:39,152 --> 00:30:40,326
Hey!

509
00:30:40,445 --> 00:30:42,913
Sale on flesh over here!

510
00:30:44,574 --> 00:30:45,867
Ruby?

511
00:30:51,414 --> 00:30:52,506
Deb!

512
00:30:53,583 --> 00:30:56,881
- What's going on?
- Get on the roof! Trust me!

513
00:30:57,003 --> 00:30:59,055
I don't trust you!

514
00:31:07,847 --> 00:31:09,520
Yahtzee!

515
00:31:12,143 --> 00:31:14,647
Did I hurt you in a past life or something?

516
00:31:14,771 --> 00:31:18,199
I just thought maybe you're right.
Maybe they'll find a cure for this some day.

517
00:31:18,316 --> 00:31:19,988
- Well, if I can change one mind.
- Hey...

518
00:31:20,109 --> 00:31:23,452
You saved a zombie, kid,
you didn't undo apartheid.

519
00:31:24,989 --> 00:31:27,493
Okay, let's go find your peeps.

520
00:31:27,617 --> 00:31:29,587
Hang in there, Rubs.

521
00:31:29,702 --> 00:31:31,754
It's up here on the right.

522
00:31:34,874 --> 00:31:37,888
Good. That's Stacy's car.
I'm glad she knew to come here.

523
00:31:38,002 --> 00:31:41,466
Yay! So glad Stacy isn't dead.

524
00:31:41,589 --> 00:31:44,852
Look, Deb, I hope this isn't going to...

525
00:31:44,968 --> 00:31:46,605
Are you out of your mind?

526
00:31:46,719 --> 00:31:49,021
What? We both agreed we're
not going to leave this car again.

527
00:31:49,138 --> 00:31:52,602
Until we get here, yeah! Obviously,
we have to get out to collect them.

528
00:31:52,725 --> 00:31:55,490
- We don't even know if they're in there.
- Trust me, they are.

529
00:31:55,603 --> 00:31:58,617
We always get together on the Fourth.
It's my dad's favourite holiday.

530
00:31:58,731 --> 00:32:01,745
Well, prepare yourself.
They may not be the people you remember.

531
00:32:01,860 --> 00:32:05,490
Oh, I have no doubt they'll be
unrelenting flesh-eating monsters,

532
00:32:05,613 --> 00:32:08,579
but I bet they won't be zombies. Okay.

533
00:32:08,700 --> 00:32:11,797
I deserve the things I want.
My needs are worthwhile.

534
00:32:11,911 --> 00:32:15,008
I'm not hurting anyone by being myself.

535
00:32:15,123 --> 00:32:17,709
What are you doing, Rain Man?

536
00:32:17,834 --> 00:32:21,630
I like to take a second to centre
myself every time I come here.

537
00:32:21,754 --> 00:32:25,812
I deserve the things I want.
My needs are worthwhile.

538
00:32:25,925 --> 00:32:29,140
- I'm not hurting anyone by being myself.
- Uh, uh... I want to be supportive, an' all,

539
00:32:29,262 --> 00:32:31,812
but is this mantra much longer?

540
00:32:37,677 --> 00:32:41,408
- Oh, man! What is it again?
- Well, why don't you try Stacy's phone number.

541
00:32:41,524 --> 00:32:46,199
Will you just give it a rest, all right?
You're like the Terminator of sarcasm.

542
00:32:46,321 --> 00:32:49,251
I drove you here, in my car,

543
00:32:49,365 --> 00:32:53,755
and you've been treating me like I'm just a bag
of wet diapers that you have to lug around.

544
00:32:53,870 --> 00:32:57,298
Well, that actually sounds less shitty
than whatever we've got going on now.

545
00:32:57,415 --> 00:33:01,638
Oh, wow! You know, I thought that
you were a cool guy back at the bar,

546
00:33:01,753 --> 00:33:04,766
but now I find out you're
some spoiled pretty boy.

547
00:33:04,881 --> 00:33:09,104
Excuse me, "pretty boy"? I have
a very masculine set of features, okay?

548
00:33:09,219 --> 00:33:11,520
If anything, my look is "burnished rugged".

549
00:33:11,638 --> 00:33:13,477
Nobody who is that says that!

550
00:33:13,598 --> 00:33:16,232
- I do.
- Your hair has not moved this entire time!

551
00:33:16,351 --> 00:33:19,031
It's thick, it requires maintenance.
You have no idea!

552
00:33:19,145 --> 00:33:22,242
You haven't taken a shower since
yesterday and yet you still smell

553
00:33:22,357 --> 00:33:24,077
like sandalwood and lilac!

554
00:33:24,192 --> 00:33:29,365
Oh, I'm sorry! I didn't mean to distract you
from being the weirdest person in the world!

555
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:34,174
God, Chaz!

556
00:33:34,278 --> 00:33:36,375
- Did you change the gate code?
- Depends.

557
00:33:36,496 --> 00:33:41,336
- How do I know you're not... one of them?
- Because I'm speaking in words.

558
00:33:42,627 --> 00:33:44,679
- What about her?
- Gimme a break, Chaz!

559
00:33:44,796 --> 00:33:47,133
Hi, I'm Deb.

560
00:33:48,925 --> 00:33:51,725
- Will you knock it off?
- You're Ryan's big brother?

561
00:33:51,845 --> 00:33:54,728
- You're so... different.
- Thanks. We think he's adopted.

562
00:33:54,848 --> 00:33:56,105
Oh, that never gets old.

563
00:33:56,224 --> 00:33:59,072
Can we please come in?
We've had really a long day.

564
00:33:59,185 --> 00:34:02,732
So, wait, excuse me, wait.
What are you? Are you the rebound?

565
00:34:02,856 --> 00:34:04,825
Oh, busted!

566
00:34:04,941 --> 00:34:08,405
How did you know, dude?
You're probably an uncle now.

567
00:34:09,250 --> 00:34:11,875
- No! No, no, that's not...
- I knew it!

568
00:34:11,990 --> 00:34:13,829
- Stacy's here, right?
- Oh!

569
00:34:13,950 --> 00:34:16,999
She told me all about your big breakup, stud.

570
00:34:17,120 --> 00:34:19,089
Looks like you didn't waste
much time moving on now, did you?

571
00:34:19,205 --> 00:34:21,756
No, that's not...
We're just helping each other.

572
00:34:21,875 --> 00:34:23,714
I'm sure you are. Huh!

573
00:34:24,919 --> 00:34:27,553
Deb, I'm Chaz.

574
00:34:27,672 --> 00:34:31,227
Clearly the more masculine
of the two Waverly brothers.

575
00:34:32,243 --> 00:34:34,479
- Good shot.
- I aim to please.

576
00:34:34,583 --> 00:34:37,942
Okay! Open the gate!

577
00:34:38,057 --> 00:34:40,193
- You need the code, man.
- Okay.

578
00:34:40,310 --> 00:34:42,066
- Do you want it?
- Yes!

579
00:34:42,187 --> 00:34:45,900
Okay, it's five, eight, zero, zero eight.

580
00:34:46,024 --> 00:34:48,195
That's... It's "BOOBS" upside down.

581
00:34:48,318 --> 00:34:50,489
- Wow!
- Yeah.

582
00:34:50,612 --> 00:34:53,245
A gentleman, too! Ooh-Ia-Ia!

583
00:34:53,364 --> 00:34:56,057
Thank you, Chaz.

584
00:34:59,996 --> 00:35:01,835
Oh! Shoot!

585
00:35:03,291 --> 00:35:04,584
Dad?

586
00:35:04,709 --> 00:35:08,422
Whoa! This is, like,
straight out of Mitchell Black!

587
00:35:08,546 --> 00:35:11,560
Ryan! Oh, my Rye-bread, you're all right.

588
00:35:11,674 --> 00:35:14,308
- We thought for sure...
- No, no, I'm... I'm okay.

589
00:35:14,427 --> 00:35:17,310
Hey, Stacy, did you meet Deb?
She came here with Ryan, together.

590
00:35:17,430 --> 00:35:21,606
- Where did you creep up from?
- Oh, I just... came with Rye-bread.

591
00:35:21,726 --> 00:35:23,612
They helped each other get across town.

592
00:35:23,728 --> 00:35:25,899
God knows what they had to do
to survive. Isn't that swell?

593
00:35:26,022 --> 00:35:27,825
So helpful.

594
00:35:27,941 --> 00:35:30,112
- Do we tip her or...
- It was nothing.

595
00:35:30,235 --> 00:35:35,585
It was just one hand stroking the other.
Friends with benefits, as they say.

596
00:35:35,698 --> 00:35:37,252
- I'm glad you made it.
- Oh!

597
00:35:37,367 --> 00:35:39,039
Dad! Dad, look...

598
00:35:39,160 --> 00:35:42,506
I've been thinking, I'm really sorry for
what I said on the phone last night.

599
00:35:42,622 --> 00:35:44,461
I've been thinking all day and I was worried

600
00:35:44,582 --> 00:35:46,587
those would be the last words
we ever said to each other.

601
00:35:46,709 --> 00:35:50,932
Could I see you in the kitchen for a moment?
I need a little help with my brownies.

602
00:35:51,047 --> 00:35:53,135
Mr Waverly? Hi.

603
00:35:53,258 --> 00:35:54,385
Hi.

604
00:35:58,429 --> 00:36:00,814
I always help him with the brownies.

605
00:36:01,850 --> 00:36:04,697
- Hey, Deb, how much you bench?
- Right now?

606
00:36:04,811 --> 00:36:07,065
- Yeah.
- Forty?

607
00:36:07,188 --> 00:36:09,276
How could you be so boneheaded?

608
00:36:09,399 --> 00:36:12,578
- Stacy's here. She's not family.
- Stacy's inner circle.

609
00:36:12,694 --> 00:36:14,865
She's been here since last night,
for God's sake.

610
00:36:14,988 --> 00:36:16,708
- She has?
- The point is,

611
00:36:16,823 --> 00:36:18,543
I spoke with the Governor on the shortwave.

612
00:36:18,658 --> 00:36:22,834
He's arranged a chopper evac at
the county line at 0900 hours tomorrow.

613
00:36:22,954 --> 00:36:27,130
- For the four of us, not five.
- I'm sure Deb can squeeze in.

614
00:36:27,250 --> 00:36:31,177
Oh! You're a big man
now all of a sudden, huh?

615
00:36:31,296 --> 00:36:34,060
Why did I not get the memo?

616
00:36:34,174 --> 00:36:36,510
Well, this is bigger than you are, smart guy!

617
00:36:36,634 --> 00:36:38,722
And you'd know that if you'd
listened on the phone last night,

618
00:36:38,845 --> 00:36:41,016
instead of blathering on
about your principles.

619
00:36:41,139 --> 00:36:46,228
Wait, so you knew last night that
people were gonna turn into zombies?

620
00:36:46,352 --> 00:36:49,033
No, no, no, no.

621
00:36:49,147 --> 00:36:51,946
These people aren't... what you said.

622
00:36:52,066 --> 00:36:54,570
They're just ordinary citizens,

623
00:36:54,694 --> 00:36:57,375
who happen to have contracted

624
00:36:57,488 --> 00:37:01,546
a parasite-borne virus that makes
their corporal bodies decompose

625
00:37:01,659 --> 00:37:03,961
and gives them an insatiable
appetite for human flesh.

626
00:37:04,078 --> 00:37:07,377
Oh, my God! The water.

627
00:37:07,498 --> 00:37:11,461
Now, Ryan, come on,
it's just a very complicated situation.

628
00:37:11,586 --> 00:37:14,434
All right? We haven't got our arms
around all the details yet.

629
00:37:14,547 --> 00:37:16,635
Well, get your arms around this,
Deb's coming with us!

630
00:37:16,758 --> 00:37:20,104
- That's not an option.
- If you leave her out, I go too.

631
00:37:20,220 --> 00:37:23,897
I promised her I would get her out of town
and I'm keeping that promise.

632
00:37:32,273 --> 00:37:33,531
Mm!

633
00:37:34,943 --> 00:37:38,039
- You can't talk, Stacy, while I'm shooting.
- I didn't.

634
00:37:38,154 --> 00:37:41,618
So you're saying people became zombies
last night if they drank the city water?

635
00:37:41,741 --> 00:37:44,209
Or bathed in it,
which explains how you were spared.

636
00:37:44,327 --> 00:37:46,664
Stacy, Deb is my guest. Please!

637
00:37:46,788 --> 00:37:51,545
I'm not trying to be mean, I'm just going by
the look of her hair and face and clothes.

638
00:37:51,668 --> 00:37:56,591
But, Ryan, you take a shower, like,
every ten minutes. Why didn't you turn?

639
00:37:56,714 --> 00:37:58,186
Unless...

640
00:37:58,299 --> 00:38:00,435
I think I'm gonna be sick.

641
00:38:00,552 --> 00:38:02,023
Hi-ooh!

642
00:38:02,136 --> 00:38:06,313
- Longest walk of shame ever!
- No, no! That's not...

643
00:38:06,432 --> 00:38:08,651
Nothing happened, we both just passed out.

644
00:38:08,768 --> 00:38:12,280
- I mean, something happened.
- I'm sure it did!

645
00:38:12,397 --> 00:38:17,534
While you two were getting gross with each
other, I took care of Stacy and her pussy cats.

646
00:38:17,652 --> 00:38:18,826
Ryan...

647
00:38:20,029 --> 00:38:22,959
You were right and I was wrong.

648
00:38:23,074 --> 00:38:26,503
I have decided to keep the nutmeg in.

649
00:38:26,619 --> 00:38:30,131
- Oh, I'm glad you see it that way.
- Mm-hm.

650
00:38:30,248 --> 00:38:35,172
Nutmeg can be a bit much at times,
but that's no reason to abandon it.

651
00:38:35,295 --> 00:38:38,509
You guys are what, trading recipes now?
And when did that start happening?

652
00:38:38,631 --> 00:38:40,719
Chaz, will you just give
your ears a rest, please?

653
00:38:40,842 --> 00:38:43,974
- Okay, yeah.
- The important thing is, we're safe.

654
00:38:44,095 --> 00:38:46,396
We're all safe!

655
00:38:46,514 --> 00:38:49,480
Oh! Holy frijoles!

656
00:38:49,601 --> 00:38:50,894
Oh, man!

657
00:38:51,019 --> 00:38:55,408
Topper? You still have that
giant boozehound on the payroll?

658
00:38:55,523 --> 00:38:56,650
Hi, Ryan.

659
00:38:56,774 --> 00:39:01,579
That giant boozehound saved your privileged
little ass numerous times when you were a boy.

660
00:39:01,696 --> 00:39:04,709
Topper, just keep walking the
perimeter or no brownie for you.

661
00:39:04,824 --> 00:39:07,707
Yeah, like when Leah Schiffer
discovered me at hide-and-seek

662
00:39:07,827 --> 00:39:10,710
and got put in the hospital?
She didn't walk right ever again.

663
00:39:10,830 --> 00:39:15,172
Leah didn't play by the rules.
Society crumbles without rules.

664
00:39:15,293 --> 00:39:17,713
- Amen, Pop.
- And speaking of crumbling...

665
00:39:17,837 --> 00:39:20,803
I'm pretty sure my brownies
must be cool enough by now.

666
00:39:20,924 --> 00:39:23,392
Shall we all adjourn to the living room?

667
00:39:23,510 --> 00:39:25,764
Leah Schiffer!

668
00:39:25,887 --> 00:39:29,767
Easy does it there. Mmm!

669
00:39:29,891 --> 00:39:32,856
Will you look at that, huh?

670
00:39:32,977 --> 00:39:34,021
Sorry, I...

671
00:39:34,145 --> 00:39:36,649
I'm still stuck on this water thing.

672
00:39:36,773 --> 00:39:39,952
It's boring stuff, dear,
a little bit too technical.

673
00:39:40,068 --> 00:39:44,789
Does it have to do with the ultraviolet treatment
process that you're testing at Waverly Water?

674
00:39:44,906 --> 00:39:48,500
What? No. Not according to public record.

675
00:39:48,618 --> 00:39:51,583
Where did you ever hear
such a preposterous fabrication?

676
00:39:52,956 --> 00:39:55,927
I keep my ear to the ground for my job.

677
00:39:56,042 --> 00:39:58,593
Deb Clarington, News Channel Seven.

678
00:39:58,711 --> 00:40:03,717
Your system is supposed to cut the cost
of purifying our water by half, right?

679
00:40:03,842 --> 00:40:07,021
That's... brilliant and ambitious.

680
00:40:07,136 --> 00:40:10,185
Well, yes, it was supposed to be
a boon for the entire town.

681
00:40:10,306 --> 00:40:13,272
And we could sell the surplus
to the bottling companies.

682
00:40:13,393 --> 00:40:17,616
But weren't you supposed
to still be in beta on the process?

683
00:40:17,730 --> 00:40:18,822
We... we were.

684
00:40:18,940 --> 00:40:21,870
Then... why the rush, Frank?

685
00:40:21,985 --> 00:40:25,247
I told the Governor that we needed more time,

686
00:40:25,363 --> 00:40:29,160
that the pre-filters weren't
catching all of the bio-pathogens yet.

687
00:40:29,284 --> 00:40:33,127
But he... he insisted that we
roll it out before the holidays,

688
00:40:33,246 --> 00:40:35,714
so he could squeeze it into the Q2 budget.

689
00:40:35,832 --> 00:40:38,466
And by "insisted," I'm sure you
mean he gave you a huge kickback.

690
00:40:38,585 --> 00:40:42,642
How were we supposed to know it was going
to be a banner year for the Ichabod virus?

691
00:40:42,755 --> 00:40:46,101
The same thing that wiped out
the indigenous Wabanaki Indians?

692
00:40:46,217 --> 00:40:49,396
- Wobanaki Indians, Pop.
- Wobanaki Indians.

693
00:40:49,512 --> 00:40:53,605
I'm supposed to be proud of you that you
wiped out the entire population of our town?

694
00:40:53,725 --> 00:40:55,481
You see that? You always go to the negative.

695
00:40:55,602 --> 00:40:56,776
- I'm proud of you. Pop.
- Always!

696
00:40:56,895 --> 00:40:58,401
Population or no population.

697
00:40:58,521 --> 00:41:02,946
Oh, come on, relax now, babe.
We've got some catching up to do! Hm-hm!

698
00:41:03,067 --> 00:41:06,531
Okay. Well, jeez, it's been a hoot.

699
00:41:06,654 --> 00:41:10,000
- But I think I need to skedaddle down the road.
- No, Deb, wait!

700
00:41:10,116 --> 00:41:13,829
- Why, right?
- You can't go back out there.

701
00:41:13,953 --> 00:41:16,801
My dad arranged a helicopter
for us in the morning.

702
00:41:16,915 --> 00:41:19,963
Plus, you must be exhausted.
We hardly slept last night.

703
00:41:20,084 --> 00:41:24,011
You know those times when you can taste
your own stomach acid? I have that right now.

704
00:41:24,130 --> 00:41:28,520
- I know what you mean.
- I'm going to be just fine, chief.

705
00:41:28,635 --> 00:41:33,391
This was the deal. We got you here,
now I'm going to get on to my own family.

