00:55:22,260 --> 00:55:25,225
I might have been a little confusing there.
You're free to go back.

941
00:55:25,346 --> 00:55:28,941
- Wait, I'm sorry, back?
- Yeah, back to where you came from.

942
00:55:29,058 --> 00:55:31,776
You can't ever leave that town on,
kind of, a forever-type basis.

943
00:55:31,895 --> 00:55:33,567
Forever?

944
00:55:33,688 --> 00:55:37,235
So you're just gonna... you're gonna
wall us in with those things?

945
00:55:37,358 --> 00:55:39,446
That's a fate worse than death.

946
00:55:39,569 --> 00:55:41,989
You're gonna tell that to your two lamo kids?

947
00:55:42,113 --> 00:55:44,165
They're four and six, Deb.

948
00:55:44,282 --> 00:55:47,130
They wouldn't understand
the moral complexity of that situation.

949
00:55:47,243 --> 00:55:50,837
Portland may be a small town, but people
are going to notice if we disappear.

950
00:55:50,955 --> 00:55:53,174
The official story is radiation leak.

951
00:55:53,291 --> 00:55:55,759
I don't think people are going
to be champing at the bit

952
00:55:55,877 --> 00:55:58,214
to go check it out for themselves,
believe you me.

953
00:55:58,338 --> 00:56:01,435
You're not going to get away with this.
They're...

954
00:56:01,549 --> 00:56:05,974
People... people are going to talk.
There's social media, there's like...

955
00:56:06,095 --> 00:56:07,935
Twerking, My Face.

956
00:56:08,056 --> 00:56:12,196
I don't think you've noticed, but
the internet's shut down and cellphones.

957
00:56:12,310 --> 00:56:15,822
Deb, you would have had a better chance
of getting out of here if you were infected.

958
00:56:15,939 --> 00:56:18,157
They're looking for case studies
out there right now,

959
00:56:18,274 --> 00:56:20,659
trying to figure out how to stop this thing.

960
00:56:20,777 --> 00:56:21,951
Wait.

961
00:56:22,070 --> 00:56:25,498
Wait! I know Frank Waverly.
The Governor is sending him a helicopter.

962
00:56:25,615 --> 00:56:28,664
- And I'm supposed to be on it.
- You know Frank Waverly?

963
00:56:28,785 --> 00:56:30,338
Yeah.

964
00:56:30,453 --> 00:56:32,423
Yeah! I do.

965
00:56:34,666 --> 00:56:37,466
The rendezvous point's right up ahead here.

966
00:56:37,585 --> 00:56:40,433
Throw a blanket over your brother,
we don't want to scare anybody.

967
00:56:45,301 --> 00:56:48,101
- Oh, God! He looks terrible.
- Oh, jeez!

968
00:56:48,221 --> 00:56:49,265
God!

969
00:56:54,936 --> 00:56:58,816
Whoa! Deb's car. She's here.
I hope she's okay.

970
00:56:58,940 --> 00:57:02,238
Was that girl ever okay?
Now let me do the talking.

971
00:57:02,360 --> 00:57:05,457
Some say shooting a gun's like an organism.

972
00:57:05,572 --> 00:57:07,873
That must be why it's harder
for women to shoot g...

973
00:57:07,991 --> 00:57:09,912
- What the hell is going on here?
- Oh!

974
00:57:10,034 --> 00:57:13,747
- Well, if it isn't Don Juan Demarco.
- No, no, that wasn't what it sounded like.

975
00:57:13,872 --> 00:57:18,213
- Prop a squat here, One Direction.
- I have very classic masculine features, sir.

976
00:57:19,502 --> 00:57:22,385
- Why is she restrained?
- Oh, you must be Frank Waverly.

977
00:57:22,505 --> 00:57:24,593
And you must be fond of digging ditches,

978
00:57:24,716 --> 00:57:27,017
cos that's what you're gonna be doing
if I don't get some goddamn answers!

979
00:57:27,135 --> 00:57:29,769
- You know, the Governor...
- Is sending a helicopter, yeah?

980
00:57:29,888 --> 00:57:32,058
- I know.
- Hello, Frank.

981
00:57:32,182 --> 00:57:34,650
I thought I owed it to you
to do this face to face.

982
00:57:34,767 --> 00:57:37,022
- You're not going anywhere.
- Governor.

983
00:57:38,521 --> 00:57:40,657
- Why?
- We screwed the pooch, Frank.

984
00:57:40,773 --> 00:57:44,119
Well, you did. At least, that's how
history is going to show it.

985
00:57:44,235 --> 00:57:48,957
I have volumes of documentation.
This whole thing was on your demand.

986
00:57:49,073 --> 00:57:51,375
My people are at your home
and your office right now.

987
00:57:51,492 --> 00:57:54,078
I don't think documentation is going
to be much of a problem.

988
00:57:54,204 --> 00:57:56,968
Why, self-serving son-of-a...

989
00:58:03,755 --> 00:58:05,724
Let the young ones go.

990
00:58:05,840 --> 00:58:07,810
They had no part in this.

991
00:58:07,926 --> 00:58:09,895
I wish I could, Frank.

992
00:58:10,011 --> 00:58:13,808
Colonel Newton, I think you saw
these three try to rush the border.

993
00:58:13,932 --> 00:58:17,111
I think you had to use some
extreme measures to stop them.

994
00:58:17,227 --> 00:58:19,029
And I think you succeeded.

995
00:58:19,145 --> 00:58:20,948
Sir.

996
00:58:21,064 --> 00:58:22,985
Goodbye, Frank.

997
00:58:24,067 --> 00:58:24,992
Wait!

998
00:58:25,109 --> 00:58:29,250
My dad has more than enough motivation
to keep quiet and I'm his son.

999
00:58:29,364 --> 00:58:31,001
- So?
- So...

1000
00:58:31,115 --> 00:58:33,701
the only wild card here is her.
She's a reporter.

1001
00:58:33,826 --> 00:58:35,499
What? I'm not a reporter!

1002
00:58:35,620 --> 00:58:38,088
I mean, I would like to be a reporter.
I'm trying to be a reporter.

1003
00:58:38,206 --> 00:58:39,677
She films everything.

1004
00:58:39,791 --> 00:58:43,753
She's documented this whole disaster
with this tiny little hidden camera.

1005
00:58:43,878 --> 00:58:46,049
Somebody's gonna find that footage one day.

1006
00:58:46,172 --> 00:58:48,260
Wouldn't you like to get
your hands on it right now?

1007
00:58:48,383 --> 00:58:51,064
I patted her down myself.
I did not find a camera.

1008
00:58:51,177 --> 00:58:54,274
Deb, just give it up.
They're going to search Otis eventually.

1009
00:58:54,389 --> 00:58:56,773
Otis? That's her car.

1010
00:58:56,891 --> 00:59:00,024
The footage is in her car.
Let's go! You, with me.

1011
00:59:01,187 --> 00:59:02,575
The car!

1012
00:59:03,898 --> 00:59:06,947
I got the glove box.
Dekker, you pop the hood.

1013
00:59:07,068 --> 00:59:10,532
- Try the trunk.
- What? No! Not the trunk!

1014
00:59:11,906 --> 00:59:13,033
Pop it.

1015
00:59:13,157 --> 00:59:15,922
Governor, sir. Mr Governor...

1016
00:59:16,995 --> 00:59:18,336
What the... Damn thing...

1017
00:59:23,626 --> 00:59:25,881
What? Holy... Oh, man!

1018
00:59:26,004 --> 00:59:28,424
Get that... get that... get that...

1019
00:59:30,717 --> 00:59:34,015
Hey, man, that was an accident.

1020
00:59:34,137 --> 00:59:36,521
That was a mistake, man.
Don't do it. Put your gun down.

1021
00:59:36,639 --> 00:59:39,688
I didn't mean to shoot him.
Come on, we know each other!

1022
00:59:39,809 --> 00:59:42,443
That was just a...

1023
00:59:42,562 --> 00:59:45,112
- Oh, this is all my fault.
- Ugh!

1024
00:59:45,231 --> 00:59:48,660
It's customary to say something like,
"No, no, no, don't beat yourself up."

1025
00:59:48,776 --> 00:59:50,698
- Words to that effect.
- Don't beat yourself...

1026
00:59:50,820 --> 00:59:53,205
Never mind. It really is my fault.

1027
00:59:53,323 --> 00:59:55,743
But I'm going to make it right
for the two of you.

1028
00:59:55,867 --> 00:59:58,252
- What are you talking about?
- Frank?

1029
01:00:04,198 --> 01:00:06,037
Come on!

1030
01:00:09,797 --> 01:00:11,553
Ruby, no!

1031
01:00:11,674 --> 01:00:12,718
Huh?

1032
01:00:13,801 --> 01:00:15,771
Go, go! Let's go.

1033
01:00:16,721 --> 01:00:17,773
Dad!

1034
01:00:17,889 --> 01:00:22,361
Ryan. Ryan, I should have been there
more for you when you were growing up.

1035
01:00:22,477 --> 01:00:24,316
I could have helped you
be a little more rugged.

1036
01:00:24,437 --> 01:00:26,489
Why are you talking like that?
You're coming with us.

1037
01:00:26,606 --> 01:00:28,576
No! Like this?

1038
01:00:28,691 --> 01:00:30,198
I'm gone, son.

1039
01:00:30,318 --> 01:00:33,533
Bit by a zombie in a God-awful sweater.

1040
01:00:33,655 --> 01:00:36,953
Now listen up. You stay
with that girl Deb, all right?

1041
01:00:37,075 --> 01:00:40,005
She's good for you. She's got moxie.

1042
01:00:40,119 --> 01:00:42,837
Head back into Portland and
stay alive till this blows over.

1043
01:00:42,956 --> 01:00:45,376
I'm gonna buy you some time.
You go take care of her.

1044
01:00:45,500 --> 01:00:47,470
Go on! Go!

1045
01:00:47,585 --> 01:00:48,759
Go!

1046
01:00:54,801 --> 01:00:58,099
All right, come on!
End it for me, you piss-ants!

1047
01:01:06,980 --> 01:01:08,858
My dad...

1048
01:01:08,982 --> 01:01:11,153
Chaz, Stacy.

1049
01:01:12,735 --> 01:01:14,705
I can't believe they're all gone.

1050
01:01:15,947 --> 01:01:20,787
Nobody left to tell me
what to think or what to say.

1051
01:01:22,245 --> 01:01:24,297
It's kinda scary, actually.

1052
01:01:29,669 --> 01:01:34,390
That time my family was up on the roof,
that Fourth of July, and saw my dad.

1053
01:01:34,507 --> 01:01:35,634
Yeah?

1054
01:01:36,885 --> 01:01:39,602
He wasn't fixing the barbecue.

1055
01:01:39,721 --> 01:01:43,019
He was in my neighbour's backyard...

1056
01:01:44,517 --> 01:01:46,522
with no pants.

1057
01:01:48,021 --> 01:01:51,283
He was exposing himself to their family dog.

1058
01:01:53,401 --> 01:01:54,908
Whoa!

1059
01:01:55,028 --> 01:01:57,364
Apparently, he'd been doing it for months.

1060
01:01:59,282 --> 01:02:00,872
Basset hound.

1061
01:02:03,286 --> 01:02:05,457
He moved out after that.

1062
01:02:07,874 --> 01:02:10,294
I've never told that story to anyone.

1063
01:02:14,339 --> 01:02:16,925
We've never going to get out of here, are we?

1064
01:02:18,009 --> 01:02:20,144
Does not look like it.

1065
01:02:20,261 --> 01:02:22,349
All the roads will be blocked
just like that one.

1066
01:02:22,472 --> 01:02:24,607
- They'll be looking for us especially.
- Hmm.

1067
01:02:24,724 --> 01:02:27,821
On the bright side, no more lines at the DMV.

1068
01:02:28,978 --> 01:02:29,987
Yeah.

1069
01:02:30,104 --> 01:02:33,568
I bet some of those workers
will be more lively as zombies.

1070
01:02:33,691 --> 01:02:36,372
Mmmm! Rrrgh!

1071
01:02:36,486 --> 01:02:38,823
Organ donor!

1072
01:02:38,947 --> 01:02:40,584
Delicious!

1073
01:02:40,698 --> 01:02:44,162
- What was that? Is that...
- My zombie.

1074
01:02:44,285 --> 01:02:47,085
- I didn't know zombies sounded like that.
- Yeah. You've heard them, right?

1075
01:02:47,205 --> 01:02:49,697
No, I haven't heard them talk.

1076
01:02:51,292 --> 01:02:53,095
Oh, my God!

1077
01:02:55,380 --> 01:02:57,800
Only you could make me laugh
at a time like this.

1078
01:02:59,467 --> 01:03:03,264
That's mostly what I remember
about the night that we hung out.

1079
01:03:03,388 --> 01:03:05,559
Was you just cracking me up.

1080
01:03:09,894 --> 01:03:11,484
No one thinks I'm funny.

1081
01:03:11,604 --> 01:03:14,238
They just think I'm strange or...

1082
01:03:14,357 --> 01:03:16,991
awkward or...

1083
01:03:17,110 --> 01:03:19,329
I say the wrong thing.

1084
01:03:21,114 --> 01:03:24,495
I'm so dumb to think
that I could be an on-air anchor.

1085
01:03:24,617 --> 01:03:26,753
I think you'd make a great news anchor.

1086
01:03:26,870 --> 01:03:31,211
Plus I've always wanted to slap the tan
right off of Brent Masters' face.

1087
01:03:42,510 --> 01:03:44,598
Oh, my God, Ryan!

1088
01:03:44,721 --> 01:03:47,734
Ryan, we have to go, now.

1089
01:03:50,310 --> 01:03:52,646
Whoa, whoa, whoa! Where's the fire?

1090
01:03:52,770 --> 01:03:55,072
You mentioning Brent Masters back there.

1091
01:03:55,190 --> 01:03:57,111
If the outside world could see
what was actually going on here,

1092
01:03:57,233 --> 01:03:58,906
the government would have to do something.

1093
01:03:59,027 --> 01:04:01,032
The people would demand it.
We'd have a chance.

1094
01:04:01,154 --> 01:04:03,657
Yeah, but how? All communications
have been shut down.

1095
01:04:03,781 --> 01:04:06,118
Phone, cable, internet, cell towers.

1096
01:04:06,242 --> 01:04:07,535
Not satellite.

1097
01:04:17,795 --> 01:04:20,264
Get the lead out.

1098
01:04:20,381 --> 01:04:22,932
Our signal goes out to most
of the outlying counties,

1099
01:04:23,051 --> 01:04:24,937
sometimes as far as Canada.

1100
01:04:25,053 --> 01:04:27,188
- Where is everyone though?
- I don't know.

1101
01:04:27,305 --> 01:04:30,520
It would be a skeleton crew
because of the holiday, but...

1102
01:04:33,311 --> 01:04:36,159
The morning staff briefing.

1103
01:04:36,272 --> 01:04:38,194
Livelier than usual.

1104
01:04:38,316 --> 01:04:42,112
Hey, that's Misty Raines.
Ah, they're still smiling.

1105
01:04:42,237 --> 01:04:46,080
She's got so much Botox in her face I don't
know if she's ever going to decompose.

1106
01:04:46,199 --> 01:04:48,334
And that's Jerry Chavez, sports.

1107
01:04:48,451 --> 01:04:51,714
Oh, and he brought his wife's
famous cupcakes.

1108
01:04:52,830 --> 01:04:54,836
Oh! Brent Masters.

1109
01:04:54,958 --> 01:04:57,805
Even as a zombie, his hair is camera perfect!

1110
01:04:57,919 --> 01:05:00,339
- Oh, is he coming?
- Uh-huh.

1111
01:05:00,463 --> 01:05:03,927
He was always mean to me,
but I'm going to do him proud.

1112
01:05:06,459 --> 01:05:08,759
Okay, let's... let's go.

1113
01:05:11,808 --> 01:05:15,025
Control room's in here. Oh?

1114
01:05:22,735 --> 01:05:25,583
We have to turn the signal back on.

1115
01:05:25,697 --> 01:05:29,707
- Wow, you really know what you're doing.
- Yeah, I have my moments.

1116
01:05:29,826 --> 01:05:32,839
- Despite my track record.
- Yeah, what does this do?

1117
01:05:32,954 --> 01:05:35,252
Okay, don't touch that.

1118
01:05:47,093 --> 01:05:51,565
And that's it! You just lock the camera off
on the anchor desk.

1119
01:05:51,681 --> 01:05:53,484
On you, right?

1120
01:05:53,600 --> 01:05:55,320
Ah, yeah.

1121
01:05:55,435 --> 01:05:57,107
Yeah, I guess.

1122
01:05:58,730 --> 01:06:01,114
- What's wrong?
- Uh...

1123
01:06:01,232 --> 01:06:02,620
I'm just, uh...

1124
01:06:03,860 --> 01:06:06,363
so used to working the camera.

1125
01:06:06,487 --> 01:06:09,371
Maybe I should do that and
you can do the announcement.

1126
01:06:09,490 --> 01:06:10,701
- Deb.
- What?

1127
01:06:10,825 --> 01:06:15,963
Listen to me. Not only is this an insanely
perfect opportunity for you to live your dream,

1128
01:06:16,080 --> 01:06:19,343
but people need to know
what's happening here.

1129
01:06:19,459 --> 01:06:23,136
What about you, Ryan Waverly?
Are you living your dream?

1130
01:06:23,254 --> 01:06:26,967
I want to be a personal life coach. So, yes.

1131
01:06:28,510 --> 01:06:30,431
Well played, sir.

1132
01:06:33,014 --> 01:06:34,225
Okay!

1133
01:06:36,392 --> 01:06:38,195
You know, I'm going to clean up.

1134
01:06:38,311 --> 01:06:41,111
I can't make my broadcast debut
with a scrunchie in my hair.

1135
01:06:41,231 --> 01:06:43,864
- Okay. I'll be here. Hurry.
- Okay.

1136
01:06:58,414 --> 01:07:00,217
Deb, are you all...

1137
01:07:01,584 --> 01:07:02,795
right?

1138
01:07:06,005 --> 01:07:08,888
What do you think? Is this okay for camera?

1139
01:07:10,051 --> 01:07:12,270
It's... uh...

1140
01:07:12,387 --> 01:07:14,273
You're perfect.

1141
01:07:15,932 --> 01:07:18,400
I raided the weather girl's locker.

1142
01:07:23,690 --> 01:07:25,529
Are you ready?

1143
01:07:29,237 --> 01:07:30,957
- Yeah.
- Okay.

1144
01:07:31,072 --> 01:07:34,915
This is how I always see them do it.
In five, four...

1145
01:07:35,034 --> 01:07:36,588
Three...

1146
01:07:38,913 --> 01:07:41,796
Good afternoon. I'm Deb Clarington.

1147
01:07:41,916 --> 01:07:44,420
It was an Independence Day for the ages,

1148
01:07:44,544 --> 01:07:47,427
as a bizarre disease ran rampant
through this normally peaceful

1149
01:07:47,547 --> 01:07:49,634
seaside community yesterday.

1150
01:07:49,757 --> 01:07:53,435
Homes were destroyed,
countless family members lost

1151
01:07:53,553 --> 01:07:55,973
and thousands left to wander,

1152
01:07:56,097 --> 01:08:00,059
in search of the only thing that would
quench their now insatiable appetites...

1153
01:08:00,185 --> 01:08:03,091
live human flesh.

1154
01:08:05,899 --> 01:08:08,663
Unbelievable? Maybe.

1155
01:08:08,776 --> 01:08:12,869
It certainly would be easier to swallow
the cover-up story about a radiation leak.

1156
01:08:12,989 --> 01:08:18,588
Indeed, for all we know, there are only two
souls left uninfected in this once-happy hamlet.

1157
01:08:18,703 --> 01:08:24,302
Is it worth sending people in to save a fledgling
newscaster and her cameraman life coach?

1158
01:08:24,417 --> 01:08:27,632
Two days ago, I might have said no.

1159
01:08:28,880 --> 01:08:31,300
But then another story broke.

1160
01:08:31,424 --> 01:08:33,844
This one easier to believe for most,

1161
01:08:33,968 --> 01:08:37,848
but for this reporter,
it's the headline of the decade...

1162
01:08:37,972 --> 01:08:40,523
woman falls in love.

1163
01:08:42,018 --> 01:08:46,775
Sure it happens every day,
all over the world, but not to me.

1164
01:08:46,898 --> 01:08:50,196
Maybe a crisis like we have here
speeds things up a bit, but...

1165
01:08:50,318 --> 01:08:53,746
I don't think it can create
something from nothing.

1166
01:08:53,863 --> 01:08:59,036
And even though this person
may not return my affections...

1167
01:08:59,160 --> 01:09:02,174
and... I am really not fishing here...

1168
01:09:02,288 --> 01:09:04,543
it's okay.

1169
01:09:04,666 --> 01:09:09,672
I'll always know, deep down,
that he felt something too.

1170
01:09:09,796 --> 01:09:13,308
So I'm Deb Clarington, saying yes,

1171
01:09:13,424 --> 01:09:15,595
I think these two are worth saving.

1172
01:09:15,718 --> 01:09:20,108
So if you're watching out there, please tell the
authorities to send help to Portland, Maine...

1173
01:09:22,110 --> 01:09:25,295
No! No!

1174
01:09:27,146 --> 01:09:30,574
Deb. Deb, I'm here. Hey!

1175
01:09:30,692 --> 01:09:34,535
Listen to me, that's the greatest newscast
anyone's ever seen.

1176
01:09:34,654 --> 01:09:37,833
Seriously, you'll probably win
a Peabody or something.

1177
01:09:37,949 --> 01:09:39,669
Am I...

1178
01:09:40,743 --> 01:09:42,546
better than Brent Masters?

1179
01:09:42,662 --> 01:09:44,501
Crazy better.

1180
01:09:45,874 --> 01:09:48,633
Wait, crazy, like I was,
like, a crazy person?

1181
01:09:51,838 --> 01:09:54,175
Can we get, like, two seconds!

1182
01:10:00,847 --> 01:10:03,184
I don't know how long I have left.

1183
01:10:03,308 --> 01:10:06,249
Yeah, I guess we've never seen
anyone turn before.

1184
01:10:12,734 --> 01:10:14,703
- Listen, Deb.
- Yes.

1185
01:10:14,819 --> 01:10:17,453
If you want me to, I could, um...

1186
01:10:18,698 --> 01:10:20,834
I mean, if you want.

1187
01:10:20,950 --> 01:10:23,252
You would shoot me in the head?

1188
01:10:24,329 --> 01:10:27,093
Well, I... What? I thought...

1189
01:10:27,207 --> 01:10:29,508
I guess it would be one tap now?

1190
01:10:29,626 --> 01:10:31,382
It was your idea first!

1191
01:10:31,503 --> 01:10:36,216
Tonight's top story, a bizarre twist regarding
a reported radiation leak in Portland, Maine.

1192
01:10:36,341 --> 01:10:40,137
A broadcast, apparently originating
from within the quarantine zone,

1193
01:10:40,261 --> 01:10:42,765
went viral on the internet just hours ago,

1194
01:10:42,889 --> 01:10:46,401
promoting a lot of people to wonder
what exactly is going on there?

1195
01:10:46,518 --> 01:10:51,737
I'm Deb Clarington saying yes,
I think these two are worth saving.

1196
01:10:51,856 --> 01:10:56,049
So if you're watching out there, please tell the
authorities to send help to Portland, Maine...

1197
01:10:57,695 --> 01:10:59,451
No! No!

1198
01:10:59,572 --> 01:11:03,997
911 emergency centres in several
states report being flooded with calls

1199
01:11:04,118 --> 01:11:06,206
in response to the alleged zombie attack,

1200
01:11:06,329 --> 01:11:08,630
with some calling to ask if the video's real,

1201
01:11:08,748 --> 01:11:12,177
while many others are concerned
for the safety of these two people.

1202
01:11:12,293 --> 01:11:16,635
A background check on Deb Clarington
revealed that she is employed at the station

1203
01:11:16,756 --> 01:11:20,813
from which she's broadcasting,
but as a camera-person, not an anchor.

1204
01:11:20,927 --> 01:11:23,940
Prior to that, she was employed
at a Lady Footlocker,

1205
01:11:24,055 --> 01:11:26,226
until she was let go for staging

1206
01:11:26,349 --> 01:11:29,980
an unauthorised sock-puppet production
of Jesus Christ Superstar.

1207
01:11:30,103 --> 01:11:34,742
A lot has been said about videos going viral
but, for Deb Clarington, it's like an outbreak.

1208
01:11:34,858 --> 01:11:38,072
The hits on her zombie-attack clip
is impressive enough,

1209
01:11:38,194 --> 01:11:42,454
but it's the number of her viewers weighing
in and creating their own online videos

1210
01:11:42,574 --> 01:11:43,867
that's truly staggering.

1211
01:11:43,992 --> 01:11:46,672
As the chairman of the Zombie
Outbreak Authentication Society

1212
01:11:46,786 --> 01:11:51,792
I happen to know zombies
and that is not real. It's too tan.

1213
01:11:51,916 --> 01:11:54,171
I can tell bad effects work from a mile away.

1214
01:11:54,294 --> 01:11:56,180
This is the real deal, man. It's not bogus.

1215
01:11:56,296 --> 01:12:00,472
Oh, that girl is my new hero.
What is going on right now?

1216
01:12:00,592 --> 01:12:04,554
Deb, if you're still alive out there,
I want you to know, you are so hot!

1217
01:12:04,679 --> 01:12:08,061
They say they're in Maine?
That's not even a real state.

1218
01:12:08,183 --> 01:12:13,486
Deb, encouraged by your example, I told
a co-worker that he is the love of my life.

1219
01:12:13,605 --> 01:12:15,657
He's my boss, he's happily married.

1220
01:12:15,773 --> 01:12:18,822
So we both agreed it best
that I look for another job.

1221
01:12:18,943 --> 01:12:22,158
Originally, I planned to debunk this vid
using basic physics.

1222
01:12:22,280 --> 01:12:24,997
Then I thought about recreating
part of it with some friends.

1223
01:12:25,116 --> 01:12:27,501
Those idiots actually think
this thing is real.

1224
01:12:27,619 --> 01:12:30,668
Is the video real in your own opinion?

1225
01:12:30,788 --> 01:12:33,374
I believe that the woman in the video
believes it's real.

1226
01:12:33,499 --> 01:12:35,552
Now, how sure are you?

1227
01:12:35,668 --> 01:12:38,172
She exhibits all five signs of a person
who's speaking the truth.

1228
01:12:38,296 --> 01:12:42,970
I expound more on this, of course, in my book
The Five Signs Of Truth, which is available...

1229
01:12:43,092 --> 01:12:45,263
What the fudge?

1230
01:12:45,386 --> 01:12:49,479
As night falls on Portland, Maine,
more questions than answers.

1231
01:12:49,599 --> 01:12:53,941
Repeated calls to the Governor's office from
this station and many others around the country

1232
01:12:54,062 --> 01:12:59,412
have gone unanswered, but we will not rest
until we get to the bottom of this situation.

1233
01:13:00,485 --> 01:13:03,119
Now how about this hilarious cat video?

1234
01:13:04,531 --> 01:13:06,203
Yes, Deb!

1235
01:13:06,324 --> 01:13:09,836
You did it! They'll have to investigate now,
they'll just have to.

1236
01:13:09,953 --> 01:13:12,717
Well, I'm really happy for you, Ryan.

1237
01:13:12,830 --> 01:13:17,671
Let's get real here. We both know in a few
minutes I'll be trying to eat your brains.

1238
01:13:17,794 --> 01:13:20,593
Well, the joke's on you then,
cos it will be a small meal.

1239
01:13:20,713 --> 01:13:24,936
Really? You are starting to look
so delicious right now.

1240
01:13:25,051 --> 01:13:27,732
And you're starting to look like
you've lost a lot of blood.

1241
01:13:27,846 --> 01:13:32,235
- Does it matter at this point?
- It matters to me. Where's the first-aid kit?

1242
01:13:33,434 --> 01:13:37,694
I think it's in the break room, but it's
too far unless we go through the studio.

1243
01:13:37,814 --> 01:13:40,033
- Then let's go.
- Okay.

1244
01:13:45,947 --> 01:13:48,166
No! No, no, no, no.

1245
01:13:48,283 --> 01:13:50,085
I have an idea.

1246
01:13:52,620 --> 01:13:55,301
Hear me, undead!

1247
01:13:55,415 --> 01:13:58,879
This man is a friend to us. He means us no...

1248
01:13:59,002 --> 01:14:01,007
Oh, God! Oh, I regret that.

1249
01:14:05,175 --> 01:14:06,515
Ooh!

1250
01:14:11,556 --> 01:14:13,691
Oh, that was awesome!

1251
01:14:17,437 --> 01:14:19,572
Ladies first.

1252
01:14:22,400 --> 01:14:24,156
Oh, wrong way!

1253
01:14:24,277 --> 01:14:25,997
Come on!

1254
01:14:30,095 --> 01:14:31,835
Stairs!

1255
01:14:58,478 --> 01:15:01,277
Deb, Deb! Come on, come on,
we've gotta get going.

1256
01:15:01,397 --> 01:15:05,241
No! Ryan, it's the end of the line for me.

1257
01:15:05,360 --> 01:15:08,574
- Okay, I... I... I'll carry you. Come on.
- Where?

1258
01:15:10,260 --> 01:15:13,203
Listen. We've had a good run.

1259
01:15:13,326 --> 01:15:16,672
But I'm starting to get hungry.

1260
01:15:16,788 --> 01:15:19,837
I can really see myself
going to town on your liver.

1261
01:15:19,958 --> 01:15:23,090
Your spleen, maybe a couple of pancreas.

1262
01:15:23,211 --> 01:15:25,892
Your pancreas is actually singular.

1263
01:15:26,005 --> 01:15:27,678
Oh, thank you, Bill Nye.

1264
01:15:27,799 --> 01:15:30,480
Ooh! Hey, hey! Stay with me, stay with me!

1265
01:15:31,636 --> 01:15:34,271
Ryan, what are you still doing here?

1266
01:15:34,389 --> 01:15:36,857
You could outrun Misty Raines easily.

1267
01:15:36,975 --> 01:15:40,937
And now you're bound to end up
like one of us or die a horrible death.

1268
01:15:41,062 --> 01:15:44,693
I'd rather take that risk than be
without the people I care about.

1269
01:15:44,816 --> 01:15:46,619
The people you...

1270
01:15:48,111 --> 01:15:52,334
Oh, you mean me? Duh!
I'm the people you care about?

1271
01:15:54,576 --> 01:15:58,110
I really wish we'd gotten to watch
the fireworks together on your roof.

1272
01:15:59,163 --> 01:16:01,442
That would have been awesome.

1273
01:16:02,125 --> 01:16:04,379
But now I'm starving.

1274
01:16:04,502 --> 01:16:05,713
Okay, hey.

1275
01:16:05,837 --> 01:16:07,225
Here.

1276
01:16:07,338 --> 01:16:09,260
Do what you gotta do.

1277
01:16:11,134 --> 01:16:13,103
Thank you.

1278
01:16:19,934 --> 01:16:21,322
Got him!

1279
01:16:23,521 --> 01:16:25,111
- Hey.
- What's up?

1280
01:16:26,900 --> 01:16:29,580
Deb, right? We are huge fans.

1281
01:16:31,863 --> 01:16:34,544
- Are you good to go?
- Oh! Wait. What?

1282
01:16:34,657 --> 01:16:38,370
You have a bite wound there. Just keep
it clean and change that bandage daily.

1283
01:16:38,494 --> 01:16:41,175
No, she was bitten by a zombie.

1284
01:16:43,791 --> 01:16:45,844
Are you talking about what
those people back there have?

1285
01:16:45,960 --> 01:16:48,131
- Yeah!
- You can't get that from biting.

1286
01:16:48,254 --> 01:16:51,718
Yeah, that is really
an archaic way of thinking.

1287
01:16:51,841 --> 01:16:55,982
I mean, a biter would have to have an open
wound in his mouth literally gushing blood.

1288
01:16:56,095 --> 01:17:00,651
Even then, it's like a thousand to one.
What are you, some kind of zombie-phobe?

1289
01:17:00,767 --> 01:17:04,361
No, no. A lot of my best friends are zombies.

1290
01:17:04,479 --> 01:17:05,736
Probably.

1291
01:17:07,065 --> 01:17:09,615
We're just messing with you.
These things are hideous.

1292
01:17:09,734 --> 01:17:12,664
- Yeah, filthy!
- But you can't get it from a bite, so...

1293
01:17:12,779 --> 01:17:15,247
Turns out it was in the water or something.

1294
01:17:15,365 --> 01:17:16,753
Who knew?

1295
01:17:22,247 --> 01:17:26,304
- You said you wanted to eat me.
- Yeah, that's embarrassing.

1296
01:17:26,417 --> 01:17:29,265
You talked about internal organs.
I mean, it got really specific.

1297
01:17:29,379 --> 01:17:32,309
- Well, I was delirious, okay.
- You sure you don't want to now?

1298
01:17:33,925 --> 01:17:37,935
- Mm, you said some things, too.
- I know I did.

1299
01:17:38,054 --> 01:17:39,525
So...

1300
01:17:39,639 --> 01:17:42,818
It's safe to assume that you like me.

1301
01:17:45,645 --> 01:17:46,689
Hey!

1302
01:17:46,813 --> 01:17:49,862
How did you guys figure out
this virus so fast?

1303
01:17:49,983 --> 01:17:53,744
- Oh, we had a little help.
- Dad!

1304
01:17:53,862 --> 01:17:54,905
Ryan!

1305
01:17:55,029 --> 01:17:58,078
Hey, Deb. What a night, huh?

1306
01:17:58,199 --> 01:18:02,161
- Turns out biting doesn't turn you.
- Yeah, we heard!

1307
01:18:02,287 --> 01:18:07,341
- But how did you escape the troops?
- Well, like I said, biting doesn't turn you.

1308
01:18:07,458 --> 01:18:12,471
Come on! What are you waiting for?
I'm already bit, you dumb pansies!

1309
01:18:12,589 --> 01:18:14,973
- Drop the weapon!
- Come on, finish me!

1310
01:18:15,091 --> 01:18:17,595
- My head is killing me.
- We are approaching.

1311
01:18:17,719 --> 01:18:21,358
- Put it down!
- Make me, you dumb-ass!

1312
01:18:22,599 --> 01:18:25,446
Dale! Chowder! Mad Dog!

1313
01:18:25,560 --> 01:18:27,114
Chaz.

1314
01:18:27,228 --> 01:18:30,076
Jazzy Chazzy. That's my Pop.
Be careful with him, okay?

1315
01:18:30,190 --> 01:18:31,945
- Oh?
- Son!

1316
01:18:32,066 --> 01:18:34,237
Pops, we play billiards.
Be cool! That's my Pops!

1317
01:18:34,360 --> 01:18:36,116
- That's my boy!
- Yep.

1318
01:18:36,237 --> 01:18:39,619
Came to save you. I wonder where Ryan is?

1319
01:18:39,741 --> 01:18:42,244
Off with his new girlfriend probably.
I don't see him.

1320
01:18:45,622 --> 01:18:48,172
What's up, douche?

1321
01:18:48,291 --> 01:18:51,672
- We're alive and we're under arrest.
- That's my boy!

1322
01:18:51,794 --> 01:18:53,135
Yeah!

1323
01:18:53,254 --> 01:18:55,141
Now, come on.

1324
01:18:55,256 --> 01:18:57,511
Hurry up and kiss the girl.

1325
01:18:57,634 --> 01:18:59,805
- Oh...
- I've got a date with the Feds.

1326
01:18:59,928 --> 01:19:03,795
The towns overrun with zombies so they'll
be bombing the hell out of Portland soon.

1327
01:19:05,934 --> 01:19:07,939
Come on!

1328
01:19:09,979 --> 01:19:12,067
I'm sorry I tried to eat you.

1329
01:19:12,190 --> 01:19:14,527
You don't have to kiss me.

1330
01:19:14,651 --> 01:19:16,620
No, I was going to anyway.

